<HL>
   SEC Chief Asks Exchanges
   For Options-Trading Plan
</HL>
<DATE>
07/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Securities and Exchange Chairman Richard
Breeden asked five exchanges to settle their differences and
come up with a joint plan by Sept. 21 for having several
exchanges list options on individual stocks.
   He also asked, in letters to the heads of the exchanges,
that the exchanges extend until Oct. 1 a moratorium on
listing any options that were traded on another exchange
before Jan. 22 of this year. That moratorium expired
Saturday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The move, which had been expected, came in response to two
plans submitted by the exchanges to create options-trading
networks. One plan -- supported by the Chicago Board Options
Exchange and the New York, American and Pacific stock
exchanges -- would create electronic links allowing options
to be bought and sold at the best price on any exchange, much
as stocks are traded.
   Under another proposal, being pushed by the Philadelphia
Stock Exchange, when two exchanges show the same price for an
option, orders would automatically go to the exchange that
posted the price first.
   Options, which are divided into puts and calls, permit
holders to buy or sell a stock at a specified price for a
limited period. A call is an option to buy, and a put is an
option to sell.
   Currently, trading in most options is allocated by a
lottery system to a single exchange, and they then can be
traded only through that exchange. The SEC has argued that
these monopolies don't benefit the consumer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900703-0073
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900703-0073.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Medicare Benefits Expand
   To Help Cover Pap Smears
</HL>
<DATE>
07/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Department of Health and Human Services
said that Medicare benefits have been expanded to help pay
for pap smears.
   Congress approved the new benefits last year in an effort
to reduce the death rate from cervical cancer in women over
65 years old. Effective Sunday, Medicare benefits cover one
pap smear every three years for most women, and more
frequently for women with a high risk of cervical cancer.
Forthcoming regulations will define the high-risk group.
Medicare pays 80% of approved charges.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The cure rate for cervical cancer, which is treated with
surgery and radiation, is relatively good if the disease is
found early. Over the last 15 years, the incidence of
invasive cervical cancer has fallen about 4% a year among
women 65 and older, primarily because of increased use of pap
smears.
   But a study by the congressional Office of Technology
Assessment earlier this year found room for improvement. Only
about half the women over 65 had a pap smear within the last
three years, and at least 25% of all elderly women had never
had a pap smear. The American Cancer Society estimates that
among women 65 and older, there will be 3,700 new cases of
invasive cervical cancer this year and 2,500 deaths.
   The government expects about 4.1 million claims for the
new benefit in 1991, the first full year of coverage, at a
cost of about $30 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900703-0072
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900703-0072.
</DOCID>
