   The New Canaan, Conn., maker of portable electronic
typewriters and personal word processors said the expected
loss reflects "charges relating to inventory write-downs and
nonrecurring provisions for major overhead expense reduction
programs."
   Smith Corona, which went public at $21 a share a year ago,
has been reeling from a series of adverse developments,
including a 51% decline in fiscal third quarter net income.
The stock fell 87.5 cents yesterday to $5.375 in composite
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Hanson PLC of Britain
holds 47.9% of Smith Corona.
