<HL>
   Freddie Mac Sets
   Mortgage Program
   With Michigan
   ----
   By Mary Lu Carnevale
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   FRE
</CO>
<IN>
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. teamed with the state of
Michigan, lenders, mortgage insurers and community groups to
provide up to $500 million in loans for low-income and
moderate-income home buyers.
   Freddie Mac figures the program will help up to 10,000
people buy homes in Michigan and will serve as a prototype
for other states.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The program offers 30-year, fixed-rate, single-family
mortgage loans with a minimum 5% down payment through
participating lenders. Freddie Mac has agreed to buy $250
million of such loans over a two-year period beginning in
October, and the state can extend the program for one year
and expand Freddie Mac's purchases by an additional $250
million.
   Under the program, borrowers whose incomes are close to or
below the state's median family income and can't qualify for
a conventional loan could spend up to 33% of their monthly
income on housing. Current guidelines allow for 28% with a 5%
down payment.
   Also, up to 1% of the down payment can come from nonprofit
community organizations or governmental or community
agencies, and another 1% can come from "sweat equity" work
performed before a buyer goes to closing.
   The program also includes counseling for potential
borrowers by community organizations that have been approved
by Freddie Mac and the state. And Freddie Mac said borrowers
without substantial credit histories can use records of
regular payments to power companies, telephone companies,
landlords and others. In addition, the program requires
mortgage insurance on at least 75% of the value; Freddie Mac
and Michigan said they would share losses that aren't covered
by insurance.
   Freddie Mac, a federally sponsored, publicly traded
corporation based in Reston, Va., operates a secondary market
in mortgage loans, buying loans from lenders and packaging
them into securities for sale to investors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900703-0006
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900703-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   US Sprint Subsidiary and Soviet Agency
   Form Data-Services Venture in U.S.S.R.
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST UT WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- US Sprint Communications Co.'s international
unit and the Soviet Union's telecommunications authority have
formed a venture to provide data communications services in
the U.S.S.R.
   Ownership in the new company, Sprint Networks USSR, is
split evenly between Sprint and Central Telegraph of the
Soviet Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications. The venture
plans to begin operating a switching center by the fourth
quarter in Moscow to provide high-speed data communications
services, domestically and internationally.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The agreement would broaden European penetration by
Sprint, which has built many of Western Europe's public-data
networks and which has been trying to strengthen its presence
in overseas markets against the overwhelming dominance of
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. Moreover, many of Sprint's
potential corporate customers are U.S.-based companies that
are locating businesses in Moscow and are demanding more
data-communications services.
   The joint venture still needs approval from the U.S.
Department of Commerce and the Paris-based Coordinating
Committee for Multilateral Export Controls (Cocom). While the
U.S. government has expressed a willingness to increase
exports of sophisticated telecommunications equipment to the
Soviet Union and Eastern Europe, it recently shot down a plan
by a consortium led by US West Inc., the Denver-based Bell
regional phone company, to build a giant fiber-optic
communications network linking the Soviet Union with Europe
and Asia.
   Sprint, a unit of United Telecommunications Inc., filed
applications for licenses to export its technology last
March, when it announced it was holding discussions with the
Soviets. Susan Williams, Sprint's vice president of
international business development, said Sprint is confident
that its export requests will be approved.
   "Our applications for export are going well, and we still
expect service to begin in the fourth quarter {of this
year}," she said. "Everything is ahead of schedule."
   Sprint said the venture will link Soviet government
customers and the diplomatic corps in Moscow to the SprintNet
international data network, which ties databases and online
services in the U.S. and throughout the world. These
customers also will be able to get Sprint's Sprintmail
electronic mail service.
   "The goal is to offer all data communications services to
residential customers in Moscow that our customers in
Cincinnati and Miami can get today," said Ms. Williams.
Eventually service will be extended to other parts of the
country as the Soviet Union upgrades its telephone
infrastructure. Overseas links will be provided via
satellite, she said.
   A major portion of the agreement is potential future
orders for Sprint's Telenet data communications equipment.
Sprint added that installing Telenet transmission equipment
on customer sites in the country will end up "forming the
backbone of the Soviet Union's first data communications
network."
   "The joint venture is a landmark in the development of the
U.S.S.R.'s data communications capability, joining our telex
systems with new technologies that will serve our country's
needs, and those of foreign interests based here, well into
the 21st century," said Viacheslav Rubtsov, general manager
of Central Telegraph.
   The new company will be headed initially by Sprint
International's director of business planning and
development, Henry Radzikowski, while deputy managing
director will be Viktor Toor, who is currently the
second-ranked manager at Central Telegraph. The remaining
staff of 30 employees will be made up mostly of Soviet
nationals, said Ms. Williams.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
United Telecommunications stock closed at $40, up 37.5 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
